## What happened

**Apple removed DSA support from its Security framework.** .NET's macOS crypto stack (`System.Security.Cryptography`) delegates to the native Apple APIs. In .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because there's no longer a native backend to service it.

It worked on .NET 10 because an OpenSSL-based fallback was still in place; .NET 11 completed the migration to Apple-native-only crypto on macOS and dropped that fallback for deprecated algorithms like DSA.

## How to fix it

You have two options:

### Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended if you must keep verifying DSA signatures)

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Replace the built-in DSA verify call with a managed implementation:

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] data, byte[] signature)
{
    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is pure managed code—no OS dependency, works everywhere.

### Option 2 – Migrate away from DSA entirely

DSA is a legacy algorithm. If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, both of which are supported across all .NET 11 platforms:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
byte[] sig = ecdsa.SignData(data, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Summary

| | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **BouncyCastle** | No re-signing needed, cross-platform | Extra dependency |
| **Migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519** | Modern, fast, natively supported | Requires re-signing existing data |
